Church.create(name: 'Santa Ana Church (Our Lady of the Abandoned Parish Church of Santa Ana) ', location: 'Metro Manila', longitude: 121.013764, latitude: 14.581953, year: 1725, architecture: 'Baroque', make: 'Adobe', region: 'NCR', distance:0 , bg_title1: '', bg_title2: 'To Vitruvian-styled To Cherrygueresque-styled', background: ' Sitting right in the middle of the busy and tight streets of Metro Manila, the Santa Ana Church possesses unique beauty and the perfect escape from the hustle and bustle of the capital - stillness amongst the noise and traffic. The church stands on a hill at the end of Plaza Calderon, and is one of only two churches in downtown Manila spared by the destruction brought about by the Second World War. It was the first church established by the Franciscans outside the protected walls of Intramuros which makes this even more of a gem than it already is - together with other beautiful churches in the capital of Manila, this church reminds fellow Filipinos alike to touch on their spiritual side despite the fast life of a growing cosmopolitan city. The adobe facade leaves an illusion of massiveness following a Baroque architectural style as it sits atop - overlooking the street. The floor-plan of the church resembles the shape of the Latin Cross - one of the churches in the country; just like the Tayabas Basilica which resembles the shape of a key; that follow a certain symbol or object. The facade is divided in three-levels with the top pediment done in Vitruvian-style scroll pattern; the second-level is composed of semicircular arched windows done in stain glass; while the lower-most level features the main entranced flanked by niches with statues of saints. Detailed ornamentations are found on niches and moldings in the cornices and apertures of the exterior of the church. A Spanish-era church will not be complete without the attached belfry, the Santa Ana Church features a four-level octagonal bell tower also comprised of adobe blocks with heavy string courses and matching ornamentations with the church’s facade. The massive interiors leads the eye directly to the heavily detailed and ornamented retablo highlighted by thirteen niches. The gold-leafed detailed main altar is done in cherrygueresque-style, which refers to the style of elaborate sculptural ornaments -expressive and florid decorative detailing which originated in Spain back in the 17thcentury. The thirteen niches are framed by solomic columns which is characterized by corkscrew-like spiral design - of course, with the Our Lady of the Abandoned as the main attraction. Contrasting the grandeur of the main altar, the dome of the Santa Ana Church which is situated just above the transept crossing features paintings of the twelve apostles and the evangelists, with the balconies overlooking the faithfuls. Aside from the abundant value the church structure itself possesses, the Camarin de la Virgen which is a chapel devoted to Our Lady of the Abandoned features heavily detailed paintings which were very-much preserved and retained from the time it was created. Another unique element is the Pozo de la Virgen which is said to contain healing waters and also enshrines an 18th-century wood and ivory relieve image of Our Lady of the Abandoned. The church was declared as a National Cultural Treasure in 1973. Today, the church stands humbly and quietly at the heart of Metro Manila.', fact_title: '', artistic_value: 9, photo_number: 12)
