Church.create(name: 'Tayabas Basilica (Minor Basilica of St. Michael the Archangel)', location: 'Quezon', longitude: 121.590831, latitude: 14.025942, year: 1894, architecture: 'Renaissance', make: 'Brick', region: 'IV-A', distance: 147,bg_title1: '', bg_title2: 'The Key of Tayabas', background: 'Built in a shape of a key, the Tayabas Basilica has not only been a testament of time and religion but also of its history with war. The church played a vital role during the Filipino revolutionaries during the Spanish colonial period and also served as a garrison by the Japanese in World War II. The beauty of the church goes way beyond the fact that it has stood in witness of history; including the fact that it is the longest Spanish colonial church in the entire country. It is also considered the bestpreserved and most beautifully-decorated church complex in the entire province. Despite being damaged by earthquakes just like other churches, the Tayabas Basilica was able to preserve is grand and innate beauty. The facade features a blend of various styles despite the architectural style being Baroque, and this is a result of the many renovations the church has undergone. In line with the variety of artistic and design styles, the main entrance is flanked niches done in Mudejar style. Lion statues greet parishioners and visitors at the front of the church - which derives from Chinese influence during the pre-colonial times, when the Chinese traded with the natives. The facade is connected to a three-story level belfry which contains an eighteenth-century clock which is known to be the the oldest not only in the country but also in Asia, as well as the only one of its kind in the Philippines. A unique and well-preserved Franciscan Seal which was the symbol of the frays who lead the parish during the hispanic era - this was a symbol of the unity of Christ and St. Francis of Assisi which can found on the wall of the church facing the Alitao River. Upon entering the church, there is a greeting of Neo-Classical design together with a seven altars throughout the church. The beautifully done round transept and crossing was the work of “maestro carpintero” Severo Carpintero. The colorful and attractive dome features a balcony overlooking the altar. A nice note to take is in 2011, the lighting of the church’s facade was converted to solar energy - making it the first Spanish-colonial church to use such technology. Just like the country’s other heritage churches, the Tayabas Basilica is not only a testament to Spanishcolonial era architecture but also to the long and rich history of the struggle and rise of the Filipino people. No matter what religion or nationality you may be, the Tayabas Basilica is definitely up there with one of the best in the country - it’s own unique beauty and charm makes it a wonderful spot to pay a visit while in the province of Quezon.', fact_title: '', artistic_value: 11, photo_number:6 )
