Church.create(name: 'Tuguegarao Cathedral (St. Peter Metropolitan Cathedral)', location: 'Cagayan', longitude: 121.730503, latitude: 17.613592, year: 1768, architecture: 'Baroque (“Barn-style Baroque”)', make: 'Brick', region: 'II', distance: 488,bg_title1: '', bg_title2: 'Proudly Featured In The Rome Basilica', background: 'Tuguegarao is home to the famed Callao Cave and Palaui Island, but a gem of a church is situated at the heart of the province. Standing still and tall in one of the hottest parts of the country, the Tuguegarao Cathedral is the largest church in the region, and does not only serve as the seat of the Archdiocese of Tuguegarao but also features great artistic and historic value. Built in 1758, it took seven years to build this proud brick church - it is considered one of the most beautiful in the country, though that may be debatable, the church has a picture featured in the Rome Basilica. From the outside, the church already gives a feeling of resplendence and splendidness as its three-level facade features a pair of White  superpositioned columns which brings a contrast to the brick facade; a semicircular arched entrance is flanked by multi-level niches; topped by the staple pediment and a centrally located round rose window. Architecture and historical aficionados highlight the church’s broken and crested pediment which is usual and typical especially to Cagayan churches. Situated at the side of the facade is the stunning and impressive five-storey bell tower, which overlooks and towers to give an admirable and unique 360-degree view of the city of Tuguegarao and the Cagayan Valley. The church is comprised of detailed architectural and artistic elements with finials, molded bricks with Marian and Dominican symbols, and Solomonic design. The interior is just as majestic with the newly renovated ceiling done in the reverted colourful trompe l’oeil style which produces a three-dimensional effect - as it guides and leads the faithful towards the massive gold-plated main altar. Despite being heavily damaged during WWII, the Tayabas Cathedral barely shows any of its scars, as it stands in its own unique and still grandeur amidst the hustle and bustle of Tuguegarao City.', fact_title: '', artistic_value: 11, photo_number:5 )
