Church.create(name: 'Tumauini Church (St. Mathias Parish Church)', location: 'Isabela', longitude:  121.807124, latitude: 17.275395, year: 1805, architecture: 'Baroque (“Barn-style Baroque”)', make: 'Brick', region: 'II', distance: 440,bg_title1: '', bg_title2: 'Cake-Like Belfry Design', background: 'The Tumauini Church attracts attention right from the get-go, with it’s unique and eye-catching facade. It stands still in the sleepy and slow town of Tumauini It gives a unique sense of beauty brought out by the contrasting colors in which the redbricked facade and the white cake-like belfry - presents the perfect infusion. Just like any other historical church, the Tumauini Church has withstood the tests of history, and damaged during WWII; but through the faithful parishioners, the church was repaired into original form. The beauty of the church also lies in the intricate details featured on the ornamented bricks both at the exterior and interior of the church. The church is known for its extensive use of different types of red clay bricks as well as its unique and delicate wall finishing and ornamentation. Taking a closer look at the bricks, the church features details of carvings of saints, cherubs, flowers, and foliage. The unique cylindrical belfry of the church is the only one of its kind in the country. The white belfry is as detailed as the facade with ornamental designs of its own - concentric circles with spiral curves on the finials crowning wavy silhouette of the facade - the cylindrical finish, features a bit of Chinese influence. Upon entering, the church greets parishioners and visitors alike with a brick finish throughout the interior. It does not have a retablo, instead features a simple altar under an ornate dome and the Crucified Lord against the brick wall - though the brick composition throughout adds a rare feel and ambiance to the altar. The interior is one-of-a-kind, and proves that the Tumauini Church is definitely well-preserved - and to no surprise, has been on the shortlist of the UNESCO World Heritage Sites since 2006. The province of Isabela will not be the same without the iconic Tumauini Church. ', fact_title: '', artistic_value: 10, photo_number:7 )
